        <h3 class="cag-h3">Which Diseases Do You Screen Our Timnehs For?</h3>
        <p>Our panel covers the two psittacine heavyweights — Psittacine Beak and Feather Disease and Avian Polyomavirus — on top of a complete avian-vet exam before the bird flies. Both spread without symptoms and kill, which is precisely why we test for them instead of crossing our fingers.</p>

        <h4 class="cag-h4">Do You PCR-Test Our Timnehs for PBFD and Polyomavirus?</h4>
        <p>Yes — each Timneh runs a PCR screen for PBFD and for Avian Polyomavirus, and a negative on both is required before the bird is placed. <a href="https://www.aav.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Association of Avian Veterinarians</a> counts both as baseline psittacine screening, and that clinical bar — not a marketing one — is the one we hold ours to.</p>

        <h5 class="cag-h5">An Avian Vet PCR-Screens Every Timneh for PBFD and Avian Polyomavirus</h5>
        <p>Specifically, an avian vet is the one running the PCR panels and the pre-flight exam, and a written guarantee — full terms on our <a href="/african-greys-for-sale-with-health-guarantee/">African Grey health guarantee page</a> — stands behind the bird once it's yours. That backing is what separates a documented Timneh from a merely hoped-for one.</p>
