      <!-- 9 · LEGAL / CITES -->
      <section id="legal">
        <h2 class="cag-h2">Is It Legal to Own a Timneh African Grey in the United States?</h2>
        <p>Yes — because our Timnehs are captive-bred, they're fully legal to own and move across state lines once the paperwork lines up. African Greys do sit on CITES Appendix I, and instead of skirting that fact we lead with it: Appendix I is the exact boundary between documented breeders like us and the wild-caught trade we refuse to have anything to do with.</p>
        <img class="sec-img inf-img" src={IMG + "own-a-timneh-legally-usa-cites-appendix-i-infographic.webp"} srcset={IMG + "own-a-timneh-legally-usa-cites-appendix-i-infographic-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "own-a-timneh-legally-usa-cites-appendix-i-infographic.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:860px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" decoding="async" alt="Infographic on legally owning a Timneh African Grey in the USA — CITES Appendix I, captive-bred, US-only shipping, no international export" />

        <h3 class="cag-h3">What Does CITES Appendix I Mean for a Timneh Buyer?</h3>
        <p>Appendix I is the tightest protection band CITES has, and for you as a buyer it boils down to one thing — captive-bred documentation is essential, which is why it accompanies every bird we hand over. Pair it with our USDA Animal Welfare Act license and you've got a paper trail no counterfeit listing can fake. Our <a href="/captive-bred-african-grey-parrot/">captive-bred African Grey program</a> walks through how those documents come to be.</p>

        <h4 class="cag-h4">Can a Captive-Bred Timneh Ship Legally Across State Lines?</h4>
        <p>Moving a captive-bred, documented Timneh from one US state to another is legal with the right paperwork in hand — which is precisely how ours travel. What isn't legal is the casual overseas shipment of an Appendix-I parrot, and that gap is worth remembering whenever a listing dangles "worldwide" delivery.</p>

        <h5 class="cag-h5">With Paperwork, Captive-Bred Appendix-I Greys Are Legal to Own and Rehome Inside the US</h5>
        <p><a href="https://www.parrots.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The World Parrot Trust</a> lays out how responsible captive breeding relieves poaching pressure on wild grey populations — a line we never cross: every Timneh we sell hatched in the USA from captive parents and travels legally within the country carrying its CITES and USDA records. Our <a href="/cites-african-grey-documentation/">CITES documentation guide</a> steps through each record.</p>

        <h6 class="cag-h6">We Ship US-Only — Anyone Offering "24-Hour Delivery to Canada or Australia" Is Breaking CITES Law</h6>
        <p>To be unmistakable about it: we don't ship Timnehs abroad, period. The African Grey was moved up to <a href="https://cites.org/eng/app/appendices.php" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CITES Appendix I</a> at CoP17, with the stricter rules landing in January 2017, so any seller breezily promising "24-hour international shipping to Canada or Australia" is advertising something the Convention outright bans — a scam tell wearing the costume of a service.</p>
