      <!-- 11 · MONTHLY CARE COST (HTML care cards) -->
      <section id="carecost">
        <h2 class="cag-h2">What Does It Cost to Care for a Timneh African Grey Every Month?</h2>
        <p>Beyond the purchase price, a Timneh African Grey costs most families roughly $60–$150 a month once you add food, fresh produce, toys and a vet fund — less than a Congo eats, but a real, ongoing budget over a 40–50 year life. Getting the diet and enrichment right from day one is the cheapest health insurance there is for a bird this long-lived.</p>

        <img class="sec-img inf-img" src={IMG + "timneh-african-grey-monthly-care-cost-diet-infographic.webp"} srcset={IMG + "timneh-african-grey-monthly-care-cost-diet-infographic-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "timneh-african-grey-monthly-care-cost-diet-infographic.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:860px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" decoding="async" alt="Timneh African Grey monthly care and diet infographic — 70 to 80 percent pellets, 20 to 25 percent fresh veg, 5 to 10 percent treats, and a minimum 32 by 24 by 40 inch cage" />
        <img class="sec-img og-photo" src={IMG + "timneh-african-grey-eating-peanut.webp"} srcset={IMG + "timneh-african-grey-eating-peanut-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "timneh-african-grey-eating-peanut.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:860px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" decoding="async" alt="A Timneh African Grey holding and eating a peanut, part of the varied daily diet a grey needs" />

        <h3 class="cag-h3">What Do Timnehs Eat, and How Much Room Do They Need?</h3>
        <p>A thriving Timneh lives on a base of quality pellets with daily fresh chop, keeping nuts and fruit as treats, inside a cage no smaller than 32 by 24 by 40 inches and with several supervised hours out of it each day. Feed and engage one well and you get a sweet companion; leave it bored or on a seed-only diet and you get the screaming and plucking that fills rescue waitlists.</p>
      </section>

      <div class="seam"><img src={seam} width="150" height="50" alt="" loading="lazy" decoding="async"></div>

      <!-- 12 · LIFESTYLE -->
      <section id="lifestyle">
        <h2 class="cag-h2">What's Daily Life With a Timneh African Grey Really Like?</h2>
        <p>Sharing a home with a Timneh African Grey is a bit like living with a witty, strong-willed housemate who never fully grows up — deeply rewarding, and honestly a fair amount of work. We raise ours to fold into family routines, but a Timneh still needs daily company, real mental challenge and a varied fresh diet to stay content across a 40-to-50-year life.</p>
        <img class="sec-img og-photo og-tall" src={IMG + "evie-timneh-african-grey-bath-play.webp"} srcset={IMG + "evie-timneh-african-grey-bath-play-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "evie-timneh-african-grey-bath-play.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:860px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" decoding="async" alt="Evie, a young Timneh African Grey, enjoying a playful bath on a keeper's hand" />

        <h3 class="cag-h3">How Many Hours and How Much Enrichment Does a Timneh Need?</h3>
        <p>Budget several hours a day out of the cage with genuine engagement, and keep a rotation of foraging toys and puzzles going to occupy that oversized brain. Timnehs are social down to the bone, so that time together isn't a bonus — it's what stands between a chatty, fully-feathered bird and a frustrated one.</p>
        <img class="sec-img og-photo og-tall" src={IMG + "timneh-african-grey-on-hand-playful.webp"} srcset={IMG + "timneh-african-grey-on-hand-playful-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "timneh-african-grey-on-hand-playful.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:860px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" decoding="async" alt="A hand-raised Timneh African Grey playing on a keeper's hand, beak open mid-chatter" />
      </section>

      <div class="seam"><img src={seam} width="150" height="50" alt="" loading="lazy" decoding="async"></div>

      <!-- 13 · EGGS (truth-forward teaser) -->
      <section id="eggs">
        <h2 class="cag-h2">Curious About Timneh African Grey Eggs? Read This First.</h2>
        <p>If you searched for Timneh African Grey eggs, here's the honest breeder answer up front: we don't ship loose fertile eggs to hobby incubators, and you should be very wary of anyone who does. Most "parrot eggs for sale" listings are outright fraud, and even a genuine fertile egg has slim odds of hatching and surviving outside an experienced hand-feeding setup.</p>

        <h3 class="cag-h3">Why We Don't Ship Loose Fertile Timneh Eggs</h3>
        <p>Shipping vibration, temperature swings and incubation error kill far more eggs than they ever hatch, so selling loose Timneh eggs would trade a living bird's odds for a quick sale — something we won't do. Our own <a href="/how-to-avoid-african-grey-parrot-scams/">scam guide</a> lists "parrot eggs for sale" as a classic red flag for exactly this reason, and our <a href="/african-grey-parrot-bird-eggs-for-sale-usa/">African Grey egg page</a> explains the incubation reality in full.</p>

        <h4 class="cag-h4">What Should You Reserve Instead of an Egg?</h4>
        <p>If you want a Timneh, reserve a hand-raised, weaned chick like Elad or Evie rather than an egg — you get a socialized, documented bird instead of a gamble. It's the same instinct that makes egg listings tempting (getting in early), pointed at an outcome that actually works.</p>

        <h5 class="cag-h5">A Weaned, Hand-Raised Timneh Chick Beats Any Shipped Egg for Survival</h5>
        <p>A weaned Timneh has already cleared the fragile hatch-and-hand-feed stage that ends most eggs, and it arrives with its testing and paperwork done. That's why we point egg-searchers toward our available birds — the survival odds and the documentation aren't close.</p>
      </section>

      <div class="seam"><img src={seam} width="150" height="50" alt="" loading="lazy" decoding="async"></div>

      <!-- 14 · CONGO CROSS-SELL (Table B teaser) -->
      <section id="congo">
        <h2 class="cag-h2">Prefer a Congo African Grey Instead?</h2>
        <p>If you're weighing the bigger, red-tailed grey, we raise those too — a Congo is larger, with the headline hundred-plus-word vocabulary, while a Timneh is smaller, maroon-tailed, calmer-leaning and often an earlier talker. Neither is "better"; the right pick is about your home, and here's the fast version before you dive into the full comparison.</p>
        <img class="sec-img inf-img" src={IMG + "timneh-vs-congo-fast-facts.webp"} srcset={IMG + "timneh-vs-congo-fast-facts-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "timneh-vs-congo-fast-facts.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:860px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" decoding="async" alt="Timneh vs Congo African Grey fast-facts — size, tail colour, beak and temperament compared" />

        <h3 class="cag-h3">How a Congo Differs From a Timneh at a Glance</h3>
        <p>Two quick cards tell most of the story — reach for the full <a href="/congo-vs-timneh-african-grey/">Congo vs Timneh comparison</a> for the deep dive, or browse our <a href="/congo-african-grey-for-sale/">Congo African Greys for sale</a> if the bigger grey is calling you.</p>
        <div class="otB">
          <div class="otB-card">
            <span class="otB-name"><img src="/emoji/cag-congo-64.webp" width="22" height="22" alt="" loading="lazy" decoding="async"> Congo</span>
